<hl>
<seg id=1> Gu Yongjiang says, Mainland Economic Development Provides Five Big Opportunities for Hong Kong Special Administrative Region </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Gu Yongjiang says, the economic development of the mainland provides five big opportunities for Hong Kong: </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> -- Beneficial for the stability and prosperity of Hong Kong in the long run. </seg>
<seg id=4> The mainland economy grows more stable over a long period of time, and Hong Kong's economy will benefit from its vigor. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> -- Can provide more business opportunities for Hong Kong. </seg>
<seg id=6> With gradual opening to the outside world in service sectors such as trading, finance, and retail, Hong Kong's service industry will gain more room for development. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> -- Beneficial to strengthening of Hong Kong's status as trading and shipping center. </seg>
<seg id=8> By 2010, mainland China's foreign trade is expected to reach US$800 billion, and it will undoubtedly increase the need for transport and shipping in Hong Kong. This will be helpful for cementing the status of Hong Kong as a trading and shipping center. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> -- Push further development of Hong Kong financial market. </seg>
<seg id=10> Along with the deepening of the reform of state-owned enterprises, more and more corporate enterprises will expand to the overseas markets, and Hong Kong will be the first choice for offshore listing location of state-owned enterprises. </seg>
<seg id=11> This will extend the Hong Kong Stock Market's scale, improve its construction, and invigorate the Hong Kong bond market's development.  Hong Kong also to gain more Chinese funds, and all of these factors will cement the status of Hong Kong as an international financial center. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> -- Be beneficial for strengthening the international competition ability of Hong Kong products. </seg>
<seg id=13> The economically complementing relationship between China's mainland and Hong Kong can combine the strength of both areas, while strengthening the international competitive ability of Hong Kong products. </seg>
</p>
